title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER ~ 1876 SECOND MODEL SET TRIGGER...SN4956, Mfd 1878...ANTIQUE, NO FFL .45-75 Winchester
postcontent: Here's an antique Winchester Model 1876 "Centennial" rifle that was manufactured back in 1878. It is a "Second Model" with the "thumbprint" dust cover and dust cover rail that is attached to the receiver with screws. Like all of the early 76's, it is chambered for the .45-75 cartridge and unmarked in regards to caliber. It wears the standard 28" octagon barrel with full length magazine. It is factory fitted with the optional single-set trigger. This rifle is in very good condition overall and still retains a fair amount of the original factory blue finish although much of the surface has light rust and surface corrosion from poor storage. There are a few handling marks as well as some fine scratching to the right side of the receiver from over-aggressive cleaning. I'd grade the remaining finish at about 30-40% overall. The ladder type rear barrel sight is marked "1876" and works alright in spite of the right side of the sight blade being bent to the rear. The stocks are in good condition and free of any cracks. There are the normal handling marks, small dings and scratches that one would expect. The rifle appears to be in good mechanical condition with everything working properly, including the set trigger. The bore rates about good with some minor erosion but good rifling with a fair amount of shine. It looks like it would certainly be shootable with appropriate loads. Essentially a scaled-up 1873, the Model 1876 was the largest of the Winchester lever rifles and had an enormous receiver to handle the large cartridges it chambered. Production was somewhat limited however, partly due to the introduction of the mechanically superior Model 1886. These were typically "working guns" which saw heavy use, many shipped out West. This rifle comes with a Cody Museum letter which verifies it was manufactured with an octagon barrel with a set trigger and "lid" (dust cover). It was shipped September 18, 1878, the second year of production.shipping is free. This is an antique cartridge firing rifle and as such, no FFL is required for transfer. It can be shipped directly to buyer.
